│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The loop-vectorizer crashes on the provided IR with an assertion inside       │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF():                                    │
│   assert((BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width ||                               │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...)) && " VPlan cost model and legacy  │
│ cost model disagreed");                                                       │
│ This assertion checks that either (a) the new VPlan-based cost model          │
│ (BestFactor) selects the same VF as the legacy cost model (LegacyVF), or (b)  │
│ the chosen VPlan contains extra simplifications not seen by the legacy cost   │
│ model, which could justify a difference. In the reproducer, BestFactor        │
│ selects VF=1 (scalar) while LegacyVF selects VF=4 (vector), and               │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications returns false, triggering the           │
│ assertion.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The pass fails early; no transformations occur. In the debugger, locals show  │
│ BestFactor is scalar (VF=1) and LegacyVF is 4. FirstPlan has only the scalar  │
│ VF recorded (vectorFactors() size 1). This indicates the new cost model chose │
│ the scalar plan while the legacy model judged VF=4 optimal. The assertion     │
│ failure exposes a mismatch between the two cost models without recognized     │
│ simplifications.                                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The new VPlan-based cost model and the legacy cost model can legitimately     │
│ disagree when neither side has missed any simplifications (e.g., incomplete   │
│ parity in cost accounting of predicated or scalarized instructions). The      │
│ current code assumes that any disagreement must be explainable via detected   │
│ simplifications in the selected VPlan; otherwise it asserts. In practice,     │
│ transitional differences in the still-evolving VPlan cost model (e.g., cost   │
│ estimation of predicated variable shifts and urem chains) can yield a         │
│ different VF than the legacy model even when no simplifications are flagged,  │
│ producing false-positive assertion failures and aborts. The assertion is too  │
│ strict and prevents graceful fallback. A safe resolution is to reconcile the  │
│ disagreement by deferring to the legacy VF when there are no simplifications; │
│ this maintains correctness (legacy model has historically driven decisions)   │
│ while allowing continued progress of the pass. This turns the assertion from  │
│ a hard failure into a recovery path, preserving existing behavior and         │
│ avoiding crashes.                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp Lines 7369-7384.        │
│ Replace the current assertion block with logic that:                          │
│   (a) Computes LegacyVF and CostCtx as before.                                │
│   (b) If the widths differ, precompute costs and test for simplifications.    │
│   (c) If no simplifications are found, adopt LegacyVF (BestFactor = LegacyVF) │
│ instead of asserting.                                                         │
│   (d) Retain a reduced assertion to catch only unexpected internal            │
│ inconsistencies (e.g., missing scalar cost).                                  │
│ This change respects the intent of validating the new cost model but avoids   │
│ aborting for benign disagreements lacking extra simplifications.              │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By converting the rigid assertion into a controlled reconciliation step, the  │
│ loop-vectorizer will no longer crash on the reproducer. The pass will fall    │
│ back to the legacy VF choice when the new cost model disagrees without        │
│ simplifications, maintaining correctness and stability while allowing further │
│ refinement of the VPlan cost model.                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
