  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe loop-vectorizer crashes on the
provided IR with an assertion inside LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF():\n
assert((BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width ||
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...)) && \" VPlan cost model and legacy
cost model disagreed\");\nThis assertion checks that either (a) the new
VPlan-based cost model (BestFactor) selects the same VF as the legacy cost model
(LegacyVF), or (b) the chosen VPlan contains extra simplifications not seen by
the legacy cost model, which could justify a difference. In the reproducer,
BestFactor selects VF=1 (scalar) while LegacyVF selects VF=4 (vector), and
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications returns false, triggering the
assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe pass fails early; no transformations
occur. In the debugger, locals show BestFactor is scalar (VF=1) and LegacyVF is
4. FirstPlan has only the scalar VF recorded (vectorFactors() size 1). This
indicates the new cost model chose the scalar plan while the legacy model judged
VF=4 optimal. The assertion failure exposes a mismatch between the two cost
models without recognized simplifications.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe new
VPlan-based cost model and the legacy cost model can legitimately disagree when
neither side has missed any simplifications (e.g., incomplete parity in cost
accounting of predicated or scalarized instructions). The current code assumes
that any disagreement must be explainable via detected simplifications in the
selected VPlan; otherwise it asserts. In practice, transitional differences in
the still-evolving VPlan cost model (e.g., cost estimation of predicated variable
shifts and urem chains) can yield a different VF than the legacy model even when
no simplifications are flagged, producing false-positive assertion failures and
aborts. The assertion is too strict and prevents graceful fallback. A safe
resolution is to reconcile the disagreement by deferring to the legacy VF when
there are no simplifications; this maintains correctness (legacy model has
historically driven decisions) while allowing continued progress of the pass.
This turns the assertion from a hard failure into a recovery path, preserving
existing behavior and avoiding crashes.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nFile:
llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp Lines 7369-7384.\nReplace the
current assertion block with logic that:\n  (a) Computes LegacyVF and CostCtx as
before.\n  (b) If the widths differ, precompute costs and test for
simplifications.\n  (c) If no simplifications are found, adopt LegacyVF
(BestFactor = LegacyVF) instead of asserting.\n  (d) Retain a reduced assertion
to catch only unexpected internal inconsistencies (e.g., missing scalar
cost).\nThis change respects the intent of validating the new cost model but
avoids aborting for benign disagreements lacking extra simplifications.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nBy converting the rigid assertion into a controlled reconciliation
step, the loop-vectorizer will no longer crash on the reproducer. The pass will
fall back to the legacy VF choice when the new cost model disagrees without
simplifications, maintaining correctness and stability while allowing further
refinement of the VPlan cost model.\n",
